{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"5427e974-1e0c-45f9-a4fb-e72ba2f104dd","content":"The project doesn't exist yet at that path, but here's how to configure `mcp.json` for a C# MCP server using **stdio** transport:\n\nCreate `.vscode/mcp.json` in your workspace:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\"run\", \"--project\", \"src/MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj\"]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- **`type: \"stdio\"`** — Copilot communicates with your server over stdin/stdout.\n- Your C# server must read JSON-RPC from stdin and write responses to stdout (use a library like `ModelContextProtocol` / `McpDotNet`).\n- **Don't** write logs to stdout — use stderr instead, or they'll corrupt the protocol stream.\n- If you publish a self-contained binary, replace `command`/`args` with the path to the executable.\n\nFor an **SSE/HTTP** transport instead, use:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"sse\",\n      \"url\": \"http://localhost:5000/sse\"\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\nAfter saving, run **\"MCP: List Servers\"** from the VS Code command palette to verify it connects.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"ed8b1941-97c5-4c43-a20e-60ddf15d0d95","outputTokens":348,"requestId":"F047:1EC1:F654E3:1190C33:69F940ED"},"id":"75250344-16dc-4f4f-80a9-5c8697a05dc9","timestamp":"2026-05-05T00:59:36.722Z","parentId":"47a426b7-ab9d-463b-83a6-572659a83101"}
